article.headline: Arizona State 79, Jackson State 48
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Ike Diogu didn't accumulate any rust during the offseason. The two-time all-Pac-10 forward scored 24 points in 26 minutes Sunday, leading Arizona State's 79-48 rout of Jackson State. "We still had a few issues in our offensive and defensive game, but overall it wasn't a bad first game," Diogu said. "Steve (Moore) played with a lot of energy -- you know, rebounding, shooting, doing everything we asked him to do." Moore had 17 points and seven rebounds for Sun Devils, who never trailed while winning their 15th consecutive home opener. The game was part of the Las Vegas Invitational, with Delaware State traveling to Tempe on Tuesday before the tournament shifts to Las Vegas. The Sun Devils play UNLV on Friday. Reserve Antonio Williams-Parker led Jackson State (0-2) with 10 points. Diogu, who also had seven rebounds, scored in double digits for the 60th time in as many college games. He keyed Arizona State surges in each half -- scoring seven of his team's first nine points and starting the second half with 13 of the Sun Devils' first 15. Arizona State led 54-29 after a three-point play by Diogu with 13:04 left in the game, and he came out for good a few minutes later. The Tigers got within 9-8 on a layup by Michael Travis with 13:17 left in the first half, but never got closer while missing 17 of their first 21 shots. Moore responded to the threat with three 3-pointers in a 1:12 span, triggering a 22-5 run that opened a 31-13 lead with 4:36 to to. "We were pleased with individuals," Arizona State coach Rob Evans said. "We didn't execute our offensive game as well as we wanted to. We've got to take care of the ball better; we had 23 turnovers."
